Moyers tells you that General Wheeler's aide — the one you've seen at every briefing for two years, young man, good shoes, handshake too firm — has been reassigned. No notice. No explanation in the channels where explanations normally appear.

The new aide is polite and efficient and has the specific quality of blankness that very good intelligence people sometimes cultivate.

You ask Moyers why he's telling you.

He says: *"I'm not sure."*

You ask Hoover. Hoover says the reassignment was routine. Hoover always says things are routine. You have long since learned that what Hoover says and what Hoover knows are different ledgers.

*(You have Lady Bird check the locks on the residence. You do not explain why.)*

- @lbj_hint_callback: Make a note of this.
- @lbj_hint_dismiss: Dismiss it. Aides get reassigned.

@lbj_hint_callback
title: A Note
on-arrival: lbj_paranoia += 3; lbj_credibility -= 1

You keep a list, mental, of the things that don't quite fit. The list is getting longer in ways you don't like.

At some threshold this becomes paranoia, which is its own kind of madness. You are not sure where the threshold is.

- @lbj_main_hand: Continue

@lbj_hint_dismiss
title: Let It Go
on-arrival: lbj_continuity += 2

Aides get reassigned. You have reassigned aides. This is bureaucratic life.

You put it out of your mind. You are good at putting things out of your mind. It is one of the skills of the job.

- @lbj_main_hand: Continue

