@lbj_hint_the_room
title: The Room
is-card: true
card-image: img/corridor_card.png
tags: lbj_party_card
view-if: lbj_continuity >= 70 and lbj_continuity_hints < 10
max-visits: 1
on-arrival: lbj_continuity_hints += 1; lbj_paranoia += 12

A Secret Service agent you don't recognize is standing in the corridor outside the Cabinet Room when you arrive for a 7 a.m. meeting.

This is not unusual. The detail rotates.

What is unusual is that when you look at him directly, he doesn't meet your eyes. Every agent meets your eyes. That's part of their training. The eye contact says: *I see the threat environment, I'm in it with you, we're doing this together.* He looks at the middle distance.

You go into the meeting. It's about the budget. The meeting lasts two hours.

When you come out, the agent is gone. Your regular detail is back. You describe the man to your lead agent, casually — tall, dark suit, didn't have a lapel pin now that you think about it — and watch your agent's face do something careful and controlled and very fast.

Your agent says he'll look into it.

He doesn't bring it up again.

You don't ask.

*(That evening, you call an old friend — someone from the Senate days, out of government now, someone who has spent time thinking about how power actually works in this country. You don't say what you're calling about. You talk about fishing for twenty minutes. Before you hang up, he says: "Lyndon, you should know you've got friends." You say of course you do. He says: "No. I mean you should know it.")*

*(You're not sure what to do with that.)*

- @lbj_main_hand: Continue

# =============================================================================
# THE COUP ENDING
# Fires if lbj_continuity reaches 100.
# Written not as action-movie coup but as bureaucratic horror.
# You are called to a meeting. The meeting does not go as expected.
# History does not record what was said.
# =============================================================================

@lbj_ending_coup
title: The Meeting
new-page: true

There is a meeting.

The meeting is called by your Chief of Staff. It is described as a security briefing, which is ordinary enough. The location is the Situation Room, which is ordinary enough. The attendees list includes the Secretary of Defense, the Chairman of the Joint Chiefs, the National Security Advisor, and four men whose names are not on any list you have seen before.

You attend the meeting.

What happens in the meeting is not recorded in the minutes, because no minutes are taken. What is said is said in the room and remains in the room. What you understand, within the first several minutes, is the nature of the meeting.

You are not chairing this meeting.

---

Later — weeks later, months later, in the version of events that the American public receives through channels that have been carefully considered — there will be an announcement. The announcement will be about your health. You have a heart condition; this is true, you have had a heart condition since 1955. The announcement will say that in the interest of the country's stability during a difficult period, certain temporary arrangements have been made. The word *temporary* will appear in the announcement seven times.

The arrangements will not be temporary.

---

The men who made this decision believed they were saving the country. They may have been right. They may have been wrong. History is usually unable to adjudicate this kind of thing, because the people who would need to testify are the people with the most reason not to.

What can be said is that the country did not rip itself apart. The war continued for several more years. The Great Society programs were largely dismantled. Order was maintained.

The rocking chair in the corner of the Oval Office was eventually moved.

---

*A note: throughout your presidency, a set of variables ran in the background of every decision you made — accumulating, compounding, occasionally decreasing. You were never shown these numbers. Nobody in the game was. They tracked something that players who read carefully might have felt at the edges: a cold draft from under certain doors, a pause in a voice on the phone at 2 a.m., a security agent looking at the wrong thing.*

*That variable reached 100.*

*The next playthrough, it doesn't have to.*

**[ENDING: THE MEETING — Seven Days in May]**

**[Restart]**

- @start: Play again


